rt, 'Sur la Renomm\u00e9e posthume de Ronsard et de Du Bartas de 1590 \u00e0 1640', ''Oeuvres et critiques'', 6 (1981) 53-59\n* Gregory, E. R., 'Du Bartas, Sidney, and Spenser', ''Comparative Literature Studies'', 7 (1970), 437-49\n* Keller, Luzius, ''Paling\u00e8ne, Ronsard, Du Bartas: trois \u00e9tudes sur la po\u00e9sie cosmologique de la Renaissance'' (Bern, 1974)\n* [[Charles Lamb|Lamb, Charles]], 'Observations on Sylvester's Du Bartas, with Specimens', in ''Olliers Literary Miscellany in Prose and Verse'', 1 (1820), pp.&nbsp;62\u201379\n* Lepage, John Louis [http://theses.gla.ac.uk/5083/ Joshua Sylvester's translation of Du Bartas' Les semaines and the development of English poetic diction.] (PhD thesis, University of Glasgow. 1982)\n* Magnien, Michel, 'Du Bartas en France au XVIIe si\u00e8cle' in ''Du Bartas: 1590\u20131990'' (Mont-de-Marsan, 1992), pp.&nbsp;69\u201380\n* Miernowski, Jan, ''Dialectique et connaissance dans la Semaine de Du Bartas'' (Geneva, 1992)\n* Norton Anthology of English Literature: Norton Topics Online, [http://www.wwnorton.com/college/english/nael/17century/topic_2/dubartas.htm Paradise Lost in Context] (accessed 11 November 2014)\n* Pellissier, Georges, ''[[iarchive:lavieetlesoeuvre00pelluoft|La Vie et Les Oeuvres de Du Bartas]]'' (Paris, 1883) \n* Prescott, Anne Lake, ''French Poets and the English Renaissance ''(New Haven, 1978)\n* Prescott, Anne Lake, \u2018Du Bartas and Renaissance Britain: An Update\u2019, Oeuvres et Critiques, 29 (2004), 27-38\n* Reichenberger, Kurt, ''Du Bartas und sein Sch\u00f6pfungsepos''  (Munich, 1962)\n* Reichenberger, Kurt, ''Die Sch\u00f6pfungswoche des Du Bartas''. 2 vols. (T\u00fcbingen, 1963)\n* Sinfield, Alan, \u2018Sidney and Du Bartas\u2019, ''Comparative Literature'' 27 (1975), 8-20.\n* Snyder, Susan, 'Sylvester, Josuah (1562/3\u20131618)', ''[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/26873 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]''\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category|Guillaume de Saluste Du Bartas}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Du Bartas, Guillaume de Saluste}}\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k1175722 ''La Sepmaine''] (Paris, 1578)\n* [http://www.samizdat.qc.ca/arts/lit/PDFs/LaSepmaine_GdB.pdf La Sepmaine ou Cr\u00e9ation du Monde]. (Ebook based on 1578 edition - PDF format)\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54453n ''La Seconde Semaine''] (Paris, 1584)\n* [http://www.museeprotestant.org/en/notice/guillaume-du-bartas-1544-1590/ Entry in the Virtual Museum of Protestantism]\n* [http://www.larousse.fr/encyclopedie/litterature/Bartas/171294 Extract from Larousse \u00ab Dictionnaire mondial des litt\u00e9ratures \u00bb]\n* [http://www.idref.fr/026838168 Bibliography from idref.fr]\n* [http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9013515?query=neologism&ct= Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Du Bartas, Guillaume de Salluste}}\n[[Category:1544 births]]\n[[Category:1590 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:16th-century French poets]]\n[[Category:French poets]]\n[[Category:Huguenots]]\n[[Category:Occitan-language writers]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guillaume_de_Salluste_Du_Bartas"}
{"title_page": "Br\u00f8ndby Stadion", "text_new": "{{Expand Danish|Br\u00f8ndby Stadion|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Br\u00f8ndby Stadion\n| image             = Br\u00f8ndby stadium panorama.jpg\n| image_size        = 300px\n| caption           = Br\u00f8ndby Stadion in 2006\n| nickname          = [[Kim Vilfort|Vilfort]] Park<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hansen |first1=Niels O. |title=Br\u00f8ndby Stadion skal fremover hedde... |url=https://www.bt.dk/superligaen/broendby-stadion-skal-fremover-hedde |website=bt.dk |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=11 October 2016}}</ref><br />\"Hell in the [[Scandinavia|North]]\"<ref>{{cite web |title=10. etape 2008 |url=https://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/10-etape-2008/ |website=brondby.com |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n| location          = [[List of postal codes in Denmark#Zealand (1000-3699 and 4000-4999)|2605]] [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]],<br />[[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality]],<br />Denmark\n| coordinates       = {{coord|55|38|55.82|N|12|25|06.66|E|type:landmark_region:DK_scale:2000}}\n| broke_ground      =\n| publictransit = {{S-train service small|B}}{{S-train service small|Bx}} at [[Glostrup station|Glostrup]] or<br />{{S-train service small|B}} at [[Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster station|Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster]]\n| built             = 1965\n| opened            = 31 June 1966<ref name=\"Barnak3233\">Barnak 2007, pp. 28\u201329.</ref>\n| renovated         = 1999\u20132000\n| expanded          = 1978, 1982, 1989, 1992, 2007\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] [[Aktieselskab|A/S]]\n| operator          = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]\n| surface           = [[GrassMaster]] hybrid grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = KSH Arkitekt & Ingeni\u00f8r (1999\u20132000; renovation)<ref>{{cite web |title=Stadion & haller |url=http://arkitekt-ksh.dk/index.php/projekter/station-og-haller |website=arkitekt-ksh.dk |publisher=KSH Arkitekt & Ingeni\u00f8r |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| structural engineer =\n| services engineer =\n| general_contractor=\n| project_manager   =\n| main_contractors  = \n| former_names      = \n| tenants           = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] (1965\u2013) <br /> Br\u00f8ndby Atletik (1965\u20131991) <br /> [[Denmark national football team]] (selected matches)\n| seating_capacity  = 28,000<ref name=\"stadionoverblik\">{{cite web |title=Stadionoverblik |url=https://brondby.com/klub/stadion/stadionoverblik/ |website=brondby.com |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> (23,400 seats)\n| record_attendance = 31,508 (v. [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]]; 18 June 2003)\n| suites              = 5<ref>{{cite web |title=Oversigt over faciliteter |url=https://event.brondby.com/faciliteter/ |website=event.brondby.com |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby Event |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n| dimensions        = {{convert|105|x|68|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n}}\n'''Br\u00f8ndby Stadion''' {{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u0281\u0276npy st\u025b\u02c8tj\u028cn|pron}} is a [[Association football|football]] [[stadium]] in [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]], Denmark and the home ground of [[Danish Superliga]] club [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]. It is the second largest stadium in [[Denmark]]. Built in 1965 and inaugurated on 31 June 1966 where it had no stands, it saw a major redevelopment in 2000 which increased capacity to 31,500 spectators, of which 19,700 were seated. Continuous adjustments to the spectator facilities have since resulted in the stadium having a total capacity of 28,000 spectators, of which 23,400 are seated. Record attendance dates to 18 June 2003, where a crowd of 31,508 were present in a [[Copenhagen Derby]] against [[F.C. Copenhagen]].\n\nWhen hosting the [[UEFA]] competitions [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]], seats are installed on the South End [[Terrace (stadium)|terraces]] ({{lang-da|Sydsiden}}) in accordance with UEFA regulations, which reduces the total capacity to 26,000.\n\nThe stadium has also hosted the [[Denmark national football team]] in five matches. Their first game at Br\u00f8ndby Stadion was a [[exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] on 1 September 2006 which ended in a 4\u20132 win.\n\n== History ==\n=== Turning idea into product ===\nThe idea of constructing a centrally located, municipal sports facility was presented by erstwhile mayor [[Jens Christian Jensen (mayor)|Jens Christian Jensen]] in 1945,<ref name=\"Barnak27\">Barnak 2007, p. 27.</ref> but at the time the sports clubs of the municipality could not agree on a common stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak27\"/> \n\nWhen a merger of the municipality's three largest sports clubs was considered in the 1950s, much suggests that these plans were fostered on a political as well as executive level.<ref name=\"Barnak27\"/> Having only one club in the municipality would enable a more rational use of a future Br\u00f8ndby Stadion.<ref name=\"Barnak27\"/> The idea of a merger gained support in [[Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Idr\u00e6tsforening]], and at the general assembly in 1962 a majority of the board voted their approval of merging [[:da:Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening|Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening]] and [[:da:Br\u00f8ndby Strands Idr\u00e6tsklub|Br\u00f8ndby Strands Idr\u00e6tsforeninger]].<ref name=\"Barnak28\"/> The latter, however, immediately disapproved of the idea, while a vote in Br\u00f8ndbyvester ended up with the same result: a 'no' to merging into a municipal superstructure.<ref name=\"Barnak28\">Barnak 2007, p. 28.</ref>\n\nOnly a few years would pass before plans of merging Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Idr\u00e6tsforening and Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening would resurface.<ref name=\"Barnak28\"/> Financial benefit was one of the main arguments for uniting the two clubs in order to play at a future municipal stadium,<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\">{{cite news |author= |title=Stadion till\u00e6g |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |pages= 2 |date=22 October 2000 }}</ref> and mayor of [[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality|Br\u00f8ndby]] in the period 1966\u20132005, as well as chairman of [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] board in 1971\u201371, [[Kjeld Rasmussen]], has since stated that he and Br\u00f8ndby's mayor at the time had decided to construct a stadium, provided that the two clubs would merge.<ref name=\"Barnak61\">Barnak 2007, p. 61.</ref> {{quotation|The closer we came to a completion of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion, the stronger grew the support of forming one big club. Its proponents saw obvious advantages in a merger, which would mean that administrative personnel and athletes would have better physical surroundings to exercise and compete, and finally it would benefit both horisontally and vertically that all energy would become gathered in one club. Eventually, it was suggested that a merger would mean avoiding a reciprocal competitiveness especially in the area of municipal subsidies||[[Kjeld Rasmussen (mayor)|Kjeld Rasmussen]], Mayor of Br\u00f8ndby Municipality, 1966\u20132005.<ref name=\"Barnak28\"/>}}\n\nOn 3 December 1964 in Kirkebjerg Salen in [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]], the boards of Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening and Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Idr\u00e6tsforening adopted an agreement to merge into one club: [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndbyernes Idr\u00e6tsforening]] (Br\u00f8ndby IF).<ref name=\"Rasmussen37\">Rasmussen 2009, pp. 37\u201338.</ref><ref name=\"64-70\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/historie/1970-1964/ |title=Br\u00f8ndby - 1964\u20131970 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Construction and early years ===\nWhen the stadium reached its completion in 1965, the ground consisted of nothing more than a grass pitch surrounded by an [[sport of athletics|athletics]] track and a spectator rail circling the field of play, a training complex featuring four grass pitches, and a gravel pitch.<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\"/> Behind one of the goals various athletics facilities were established, as the club shared the stadium with Br\u00f8ndby Atletik.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=1. etape - 1965: Masser af luft |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/1-etape-1965/ |publisher=brondby.com |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> In addition, a changing room with four separate compartments was constructed, featuring showers and toilet facilities.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/><ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\"/> \n\nThe official inauguration of the pitch was officially planned for late Summer 1965, but issues with making the grass grow postponed the launch to 31 July 1966.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/>\n\nIn the following years, the area around Br\u00f8ndby Stadion continuously developed and expanded; in 1969\u201370 the municipality constructed additional training pitches South of the ground, close to the [[Danish national road 21|Holb\u00e6k Motorway]],<ref name=\"Barnak33\">Barnak 2007, p. 33</ref> and even more training complexes were built South of the motorway in 1972\u201374.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/>\n\nConditions around the main playing pitch were also improved; in 1966 two [[turnstile]]s were set up at the stadium entrance,<ref name=\"Barnak33\"/> and in 1969 a clock was added, courtesy of local [[watchmaker]] Bent Henriksen from [[Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Torv]].<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/> In 1973 the municipality allocated [[Danish krone|DKK]] 20,000 to set up a modern loudspeaker system consisting of four ''folded'' [[horn loudspeaker]]s suspended on four-metre steel trusses.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/>\n\n=== Constructing the stands ===\nAs [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] moved up the ranks, a need arose for a more contemporary stadium. In 1975, the [[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality|municipality]] allowed the club to improve spectator facilities by installing two-step terraces around the [[running track]].<ref name=\"Barnak72\">Barnak 2007, p. 72</ref> This happened despite the club's wishes to install a covered grandstand.<ref name=\"Barnak72\"/>\n\nOnly in 1977, when the club reached promotion to the third highest football league in Denmark, the [[Danish 2nd Division]], did the municipality decide that a covered grandstand should be erected.<ref name=\"Barnak73\"/> The [[Danish krone|DKK]] 4 million project broke ground during the summer of 1978, and in early 1979 the grandstand was ready for use.<ref name=\"Barnak73\">Barnak 2007, p. 73</ref> The stand, which could hold 1,335 seated spectators, and included a [[announcer|speaker]] booth, media facilities and a TV plateau, was placed facing West towards [[Gildh\u00f8j (Br\u00f8ndby Municipality)|Gildh\u00f8jskolen]].<ref name=\"Barnak73\"/> Beneath the stand were constructed four dressing rooms, a kiosk, an office, toilet facilities, a storage room as well as the club room of Br\u00f8ndby Atletik.<ref name=\"Barnak73\"/> In the spring of 1980, the municipality installed the first floodlights with a brightness of 4 x 24&nbsp;kW.<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\"/> With the new stand, spectator capacity increased to 5,000.<ref name=\"Barnak72\"/>\n\nAs Br\u00f8ndby IF had reached promotion to the highest football league in Denmark in the fall of 1981, then known as the [[Danish Superliga|1st Division]], mayor Kjeld Rasmussen proclaimed that a covered stand would be constructed.<ref name=\"Barnak80\">Barnak 2007, p. 80</ref> Prior to the [[1982 Danish 1st Division|1982 season]] &ndash; Br\u00f8ndby's first on the highest level &ndash; concrete [[Terrace (stadium)|terraces]] were installed opposite the existing grandstand, consisting of 13 rows of terraces the length of the pitch in open air.<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg2\">{{cite news |author= |title=Stadion till\u00e6g |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |date=22 October 2000 }}</ref> This allowed a crowd of 5,000 additional people,<ref name=\"3. etape\">{{cite news |author= |title=3. etape - 1982: St\u00e5pladser til folket |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/3-etape-1982/ |publisher=brondby.com |pages= |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> bringing the total capacity to 10,000.\n\n[[File:Br\u00f8ndby_Stadion_2005-04.jpg|thumb|left|Br\u00f8ndby Stadion as seen from the South in 2005.]]\nAfter the club had established itself in the top of [[Football in Denmark|Danish football]] during the 1980s, Br\u00f8ndby IF reached a hitherto zenith by reaching the [[1990\u201391_UEFA_Cup#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]] of the [[1990\u201391 UEFA Cup]].<ref name=\"FiB07\">{{cite web|url=https://brondby.com/nyhed/2007/03/20/fra-mark-til-arena|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=Fra mark til Arena|date=20 March 2007|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Rasmussen205207\">Rasmussen 2009, pp. 205\u2013207.</ref> At that time, Br\u00f8ndby Stadion did not live up to international standards to host matches at that level. However, this was solved by installing temporary end stands of [[scaffolding]], which allowed the club to receive an approval by the [[UEFA]] to organise the home leg against [[FC Torpedo Moscow|Torpedo Moscow]].<ref name=\"FiB07\"/> The changes raised the total capacity to 15,000 spectators, and the club even outdid themselves when they reached the [[1990\u201391_UEFA_Cup#Semi-finals|semi-finals]] by increasing the capacity to 17,000&ndash;18,000.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=5. etape - 1991: Den usl\u00e5elige stadionrekord |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/4-etape-1989/ |publisher=brondby.com |pages= |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> In the same period Br\u00f8ndby IF submitted a bid to host the [[Denmark national football team]] at a new national stadium; a \"''Stadion Danmark''\", which would seat 60,000 spectators and border the [[Danish national road 21|Holb\u00e6k Motorway]].<ref name=\"FiB07\" /> These plans, however, never came to fruition as [[Parken Stadium]] won the bid and eventually became the national stadium.<ref>{{cite web |title=Parken, Danmarks Nationalstadion |url=https://www.cfmoller.com/p/-da/Parken-Danmarks-Nationalstadion-i34.html# |website=cfmoller.com |publisher=[[C. F. M\u00f8ller Architects]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs Br\u00f8ndby IF gained domestic and European success, spectator interest had grown to such a degree, that it became necessary to move the biggest matches to [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]].<ref name=\"4. etape\">{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415020824/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=77 |title=4. etape - 1989-1990 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |date=1 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415020824/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=77 |archivedate=15 August 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2020 }}</ref> This solution was not deemed satisfactory for neither club, fans nor sponsors, who wanted to remain rooted in the local community.<ref name=\"4. etape\"/><ref name=\"FiB07\"/> Therefore, the board under leadership of [[Per Bjerregaard]], decided to plan an expansion of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\">Barnak 2007, pp. 139-140</ref> The first step was taken in 1990, when the stand opposite the grandstand was covered and expanded with eight rows, holding 3,500 seated spectators, as well as terracing holding 10,500 standing spectators in total.<ref name=\"BT 1991-03-12\">{{cite news |title=B.T. tester de 10 Superliga stadion |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=12 March 1991 |page=2 }}</ref> In the same year the grandstand was expanded with a lounge for sponsors in which a panoramic window allowed for a view of the entire pitch.<ref name=\"FiB07\"/> While Br\u00f8ndby Municipality had financed the new covered stand, Br\u00f8ndby IF funded the construction of the sponsors lounge.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/>\n\nDespite improved spectator facilities, the stadium did still not live up to UEFA requirements,<ref name=\"6. etape\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/6-etape-1992/ |title=6. etape - 1992 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> and the club wished to erect permanent terracing behind both goals.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> As this would mean that the running track around the pitch had to be demolished, and that Br\u00f8ndby Atletik would have to be compensated with a new running track elsewhere,<ref name=\"BT-1991-06-12\">{{cite news |last=Fredberg |first=Peter |title=Vi ofrer ikke atletikken |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=12 June 1991 |page=34 }}</ref> the municipality chose to turn down Br\u00f8ndby IF's application to further expand the stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\">Barnak 2007, pp. 139-140</ref> This made the club consider moving to another city where it would be able to host international games,<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> prompting the municipality to offer Br\u00f8ndby IF to acquire the stadium and thus raise money to construct an athletics stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> The club board, spearheaded by Bjerregaard, was, however, only interested in purchasing the area behind the two goals.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> Br\u00f8ndby IF had meanwhile offered to pay for construction costs of the end stands themselves, but in order to do so the pitch had to be expanded both in width and length.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/>\n\nIn 1991, the municipal council decided that Br\u00f8ndby IF should have the sole right to use the stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak140141\">Barnak 2007, pp. 140-141</ref> Thus, a green light was finally given to turn Br\u00f8ndby Stadion into a [[Soccer-specific stadium|football-specific stadium]]. In December 1991, the contractor began removing the running track,<ref name=\"Barnak140141\"/> and in the spring of 1992, the expanded Br\u00f8ndby Stadion has reached completion: four covered stands with a total capacity of almost 21,000 spectators.<ref name=\"BT 1991-02-13\">{{cite news |last=Fredberg |first=Peter |title=Nu f\u00e5r Br\u00f8ndby sit Super-Stadion |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid|B.T.]] |date=13 February 1991 |page=33 }}</ref><ref name=\"BT 1991-08-07\">{{cite news |last=Uno |first=Steeb |title=Br\u00f8ndby f\u00e5r sit EC-stadion |work=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=7 August 1991 |page=28 }}</ref> This included the infamous terraced \"South Side\"-end ({{lang-da|Sydsiden}}) &ndash; then known as ''[[Faxe Brewery|Faxe]] Tribunen'' for sponsorship reasons &ndash; which was inaugurated on 29 March 1992.<ref name=\"6. etape\"/> With the 1,335 seats on the main grandstand and another 3,000 new seats on the lower side of the opposite stand, the stadium could hold more than 6,000 seated spectators.<ref name=\"Barnak141\">Barnak 2007, p. 141</ref>\n\n=== 1999\u20132000 expansion ===\nDespite several expansions and improvements over the years, Br\u00f8ndby Stadion could still not achieve acceptable capacity for international matches, and the club was therefore forced to rent [[Parken Stadium]] in [[Indre \u00d8sterbro]] &ndash; home of the [[Denmark national football team|national team]] as well as archrivals [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]] &ndash; for major matches under [[UEFA]].<ref name=\"6. etape\"/> This resulted in losses; both on a financial level, but also in terms of prestige, and because of this the board continued to work on plans of further expanding the stadium.<ref name=\"6. etape\"/>\n\nThe first step was commencing negotiations with [[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality]] in order to secure the total acquisition of the stadium, and as a result of the proceedings, [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] [[Aktieselskab|A/S]] purchased Br\u00f8ndby Stadion for [[Danish krone|DKK]] 23.5 million in May 1998.<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-05-14\">{{cite news |title=Br\u00f8ndby k\u00f8ber eget stadion for 23,5 mio - BIF |work=[[Reuters]] |date=14 May 1998 }}</ref><ref>Storm & Thomsen 2016, p. 278</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Larsen |first1=Christian W. |title=Br\u00f8ndby f\u00e5r eget stadion |publisher=[[Aktuelt]] |date=14 May 1998}}</ref> From this, DKK 16 million was to be deducted for the two end stands and the sponsors lounge,<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-05-14\"/> which the club itself had financed, resulting in a final amount of DKK 7.3 million.<ref name=\"Barnak180\">Barnak 2007, p. 180</ref>\n\nThe acquisition officially took place on 1 January 1999,<ref name=\"Barnak180\"/> after which the largest expansion of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion could commence;<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-11-02\">{{cite news |title=Kapitaludvidelse i Br\u00f8ndby 2 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2 November 1998 }}</ref> a connected upper stand supported by a total of 32 concrete [[Staircase tower|staircase towers]],<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> and a new roof carried by a total of 32 m tall iron structures, each 25 m apart.<ref name=\"Barnak180\"/> These would &ndash; together with the existing lower stands &ndash; ensure that the stadium could bring the total spectator capacity to more than 30,000 for [[UEFA|European games]] and 33,000 to [[Danish Superliga|domestic]] matches.<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-10-19\">{{cite news |title=Nyt stadion \u00f8ger Br\u00f8ndby-res 15-20 mio - prospekt |work=[[Reuters]] |date=19 October 1998 }}</ref> The total costs for the expansion were DKK 270 million,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_069yfp0l4ln18ma686z5_34271.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2000|pages=10-11|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> 40 million more than original estimates due to costs spiralling.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_wumjjipadudjnqgt2xau_34260.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2001|page=9 }}</ref> In addition to the new upper stand section, the main grandstand was expanded with a superstructure.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pedersen|first=Flemming|title=Ny tribune st\u00e5r klar til n\u00e6ste \u00e5r|date=2 September 1998|publisher=Politiken, section 1 page 19}}</ref> Not least, the sponsor and lounge areas were expanded considerably,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> and a new three-storey annex providing administrative offices, press facilities, commercial kitchen and lounge areas able to host more than 3,000 was erected facing the parking lot.<ref name=\"Barnak181\">Barnak 2007, p. 181</ref> On the ground floor were constructed additional facilies, including a lobby, a gym for the players and a fanshop.<ref name=\"Barnak181\"/>\n[[File:Br\u00f8ndby_Stadion.JPG|thumb|right|Aerial view of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion.]]\n\nThe connected upper stands meant that the corners of the stadium became partly enclosed, and toilet stalls as well as food and drink outlets were placed in the spaces between the lower and upper stands.<ref name=\"Barnak181\"/> The new upper stands included 13,600 new seats, increasing the total capacity to 31,500 spectators.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> For international matches, capacity was limited to 26,500 spectators as they demand [[all-seater|all-seated]] crowds.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> The entire redevelopment was carried out while the club still played its home games at the stadium, and the original changing rooms under the main grandstand, originating from 1978, were retained.<ref name=\"Barnak181\"/>\n\nThe stadium officially reopened with a ceremony on 22 October 2000,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> followed by an [[exhibition game]] between the [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] team from 1989 and [[:da:Skagen Idr\u00e6ts Klub|Skagen IK]]; a rematch mirroring a [[1986\u201387 Danish Cup]] game, where Skagen from the Danish fifth tier knocked out Br\u00f8ndby after a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty-shootout]], in what has been described as \"the biggest sensation in Danish Cup history\".<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Videb\u00e6k |first1=Klaus |title=Da Skagen IK slog Br\u00f8ndby: 'Det st\u00f8rste jeg har oplevet i mit sportsliv' |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/regionale/nordjylland/da-skagen-ik-slog-broendby-det-stoerste-jeg-har-oplevet-i-mit |website=dr.dk |publisher=[[Danmarks Radio]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=27 April 2017}}</ref> The first competitive game after the rebuild occurred on 22 October 2000 with a 4&ndash;2 league win over [[Akademisk Boldklub]] in front of 28,416 spectators.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rachlin |first1=Michael |title=Br\u00f8ndbys dejlige dag |url=https://jyllands-posten.dk/indland/kbh/ECE3300722/Br%C3%B8ndbys-dejlige-dag/ |website=jyllands-posten.dk |publisher=[[Jyllands-Posten]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=22 October 2000}}</ref> \n\nThe stadium reached total completion in 2001.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> The redevelopment also made Br\u00f8ndby Stadion a part of the Nordic countries' [[UEFA Euro 2008 bids|bid]] for hosting the [[UEFA Euro 2008]], which was eventually awarded to [[Austria]]\u2013[[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Austria-Switzerland to host Euro 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/2569017.stm |website=bbc.co.uk/sport |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=12 December 2002}}</ref>\n\n=== Additions and improvements ===\nBecause the total costs of the 1999\u20132000 expansion exceeded the originally planned budget by [[Danish krone|DKK]] 30\u201340 million, some major and minor additions and improvements to audience facilities were postponed and subsequently carried out over time.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2001\"/><ref name=\"Barnak181\"/> First of foremost, the club could not afford new turnstiles, and a planned, highly modern entrance system was only installed in 2003, just as the scoreboards initally did not meet the requirements of the [[Danish Football Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apps.infomedia.dk/mediearkiv/link?articles=e008d0b4 |title=11 superligastadions dumpet |publisher=[[Ritzau]] |date=30 June 2003 |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> The original substitutes' benches in the [[technical area]] likewise had to be utilised for some years before being permanently replaced by benches below pitch-level in 2005.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_vrizkpoxn3iharmmlzhm_36880.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2005|accessdate=17January 2015|page=19}}</ref>\n\nThe new blue seats planned for the lower stands would initially have to wait; firstly, the old, worn-out seats were retained on the two original longside stands, which in the first years following the rebuild appeared as gray, red, yellow and light blue seats. Secondly, seats were expected to be fitted to the extended section of the old grandstand and the lower section of the northern end stand. However, an extra \"row 34\" was added relatively quickly all the way around the top of the stands, in front of the glass partitions.\n\nAs new dark blue seats were installed on the aforementioned areas in 2003, a total seating capacity reached 23,400. This increased total stadium capacity to 29,000,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2003\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_vrj7ojvt3bb7yet69qvf_34266.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2003|accessdate=17 January 2015|page=11}}</ref> while the stadium could hold crowds of 26,144 for international matches.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2003\"/> This was due to the fact that for international fixtures, the South Side-end [[Terrace (stadium)|terracing]] could be converted into approximately 2,600 seats.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lassen |first1=Kurt |title=St\u00e5drengene fra Vestegnen |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/sport/staadrengene-fra-vestegnen |website=berlingske.dk |publisher=[[Berlingske]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=13 March 2004}}</ref> Despite many delayed improvements to the stadium, the redevelopment in 2000 already had already secured improved facilities for wheelchair users, as a wheelchair lift had been installed at the southern end of the East Stand.<ref name=\"stadionoverblik\" />\n\nIn 2006\u20132007, the East Stand (today known as ''GSV Stand'' ({{lang-da|GSV-tribunen}}) for sponsorship reasons) was further expanded at the back with a lounge for sponsors, classrooms for [[:da:Br\u00f8ndby Gymnasium|Br\u00f8ndby Gymnasium]] ([[Secondary education in Denmark|general upper secondary education]]), a public gym, a production kitchen and the sports bar \"''1964''\".<ref name=\"RB B\u00f8rsen 2006-03-07\">{{cite news |title=Br\u00f8ndby opf\u00f8rer ny bygning p\u00e5 Br\u00f8ndby Stadion for 90 mio (Opd) |publisher=[[B\u00f8rsen]] |date=7 March 2006 }}</ref><ref name=\"9. etape\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/9-etape-2007/ |title=9. etape - 2007 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 }}</ref> In addition, spectator conditions were improved upon with six new multi-stalls and three new staircases beneath the East Stand.<ref name=\"9. etape\"/> Two large [[Light-emitting diodes|LED]] screens were also installed during this period.<ref name=\"9. etape\"/> The total cost of the project ran up to DKK 90 million.<ref name=\"RB B\u00f8rsen 2006-03-07\"/>\n\nIn 2008, major sponsor [[:da:Jesper Laustrup Nielsen|Jesper \"Kasi-Jesper\" Nielsen]] of [[:da:KasiGroup|KasiGroup]] financed a decoration of the Br\u00f8ndby Stadion facade;<ref name=\"BT 2014-12-03\">{{cite news |last=Holm |first=Emil Broo |title=Gaver til f\u00f8dselaren: Det har Br\u00f8ndby modtaget gennem tiden |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=3 December 2014 }}</ref> yellow, illuminated letters with the stadium name affixed between the roof and the top row of seating at three of the stands.<ref name=\"10. etape\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/10-etape-2008/ |title=10. etape - 2008 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=8 December 2012 }}</ref> In addition, each [[gable]] was adorned with four large images that showed [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] players and fans in different situations.<ref name=\"10. etape\"/>\n\nDuring the winter break in of the [[2017\u201318 Br\u00f8ndby IF season|2017\u201318 season]], the hole on the South Side-end was closed which meant that an additional 75 seats and extra capacity for 150 standing spectators on terracing were added to the stadium.<ref name=\"TipsSyd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tipsbladet.dk/nyhed/superliga/broendby-fans-betaler-selv-ombygning-af-sydsiden|title=Br\u00f8ndby-fans betaler selv ombygningen af Sydsiden|work=[[Tipsbladet]]|date=22 December 2017|accessdate=23 April 2018|author=Lasse Sylvest Mikkelsen}}</ref> The rebuild was financed by the club's fans, through the official fanclub ''[[Br\u00f8ndby_IF#Support|Br\u00f8ndby Support]]'' and various unofficial fan groups,<ref name=\"TipsSyd\"/> and through a so-called \"fan fund\" which arose as a result of season tickets and merchandise sales, among other things.<ref name=\"VaerMed\">{{cite web|url=https://brondby.com/nyhed/2017/12/13/vaer-med-til-at-forbedre-sydsiden|title=V\u00e6r med til at forbedre Sydsiden|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=23 April 2018|work=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]}}</ref> In total, the renovation costs amounted to DKK 450,000, of which the fan fund accounted for DKK 270,000.<ref name=\"TipsSyd\"/><ref name=\"VaerMed\"/> In the summer of 2018, new 256 LED floodlights were installed, produced in China.<ref name=\"Lys2018\">{{cite web|url=https://brondby.com/nyhed/2018/07/10/454399|title=Nyt lys skal langtidssikre Br\u00f8ndby Stadion|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=11 July 2018|work=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]}}</ref>\n\n== Structure and facilities ==\nThe Br\u00f8ndby Stadion pitch is surrounded by four covered stands, officially known as Sydsiden (South), GSV-tribunen (East), J. Jensen-tribunen (North) and Carlsberg-tribunen (West). Three stands are all-seaters (except the away section on the North End) while the South End is terracing. Each stand has two tiers.\n\n=== Sydsiden (South End) ===\nSydsiden, literally \"South Side\" in English, was inaugurated as the new South Stand on 29 March 1992 in a match against [[Lyngby Boldklub]], due to a rise in interest for Br\u00f8ndby IF.<ref name=\"FiB07\"/><ref name=Sydsiden2>{{cite web |url=https://sydsiden.brondby.com/ |title=Sydsiden 25 \u00e5r |date=15 March 2017 |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |accessdate=15 March}}</ref> The lower part of the stand has a standing capacity of 5,600 spectators. Initially, spectators would sit on the terraces,<ref name=Sydsiden>{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/nyhed/2017/03/14/de-foerste-aar-paa-sydsiden |title=De F\u00f8rste \u00c5r P\u00e5 Sydsiden |date=15 March 2017 |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> but younger fans would begin encouraging all fans on Sydsiden to stand up, because they thought that it was easier to sing while standing, which would evolve into the mantra \"sing or piss off\" ({{lang-da|syng eller skrid}}).<ref name=Sydsiden/> This would mark the beginning of a hard-core fan-culture formation on Sydsiden, which has remained ever since, and it is known as the stand in Denmark with the most dedicated and loudest fans when Br\u00f8ndby plays its home games.<ref name=\"6. etape\"/>\n\nUntil 6 March 2011, Sydsiden was known by its sponsor name, \"Faxe Tribunen\", a subsidiary of [[Royal Unibrew]]. This had to change as there was a conflict of interest as [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg]] moved in as new sponsors. Sydsiden was chosen by a panel representing a broad section of the active fan base at Br\u00f8ndby Stadion, as fans had called the stand this before.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/nyhed/2011/01/18/faxe-tribunen-bliver-til-sydsiden |title=Faxe-tribunen bliver til Sydsiden |date=18 January 2011 |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> Halfway through the 2017\u201318 season, the hole in the middle of the stand was partly closed, after continuous requests by fans.<ref name=\"VaerMed\"/>\n\nA permanent fanzone was inaugurated outside Sydsiden in 2018 for spectators and fans before, during and after the games. The fanzone is the first of its kind in Scandinavia, and consists of stands for live concerts, bars, foodstands and toilet facilities.\n\nSydsiden popularised the \"Fenerbah\u00e7e greeting\" in Denmark, imported through the transfer of [[Brian Steen Nielsen]] to the Turkish club. A cooperation between goalkeeper [[Mogens Krogh]] and [[Br\u00f8ndby IF#Support|Br\u00f8ndby Support]] effectually made the greeting get foothold in Denmark.<ref name=Sydsiden/>\n\n=== North End ===\nThe North Stand, now known as \"J. Jensen-tribunen\" for sponsorship reasons, was originally known as \"da:OBS!-tribunen\". The lower section of the stand was constructed in 1992 as terracing, and has among fans been known as \"P\u00f8lseenden\" ({{lang-da|[[:da:Rosinen i p\u00f8lseenden|the sausage end]]}}) due to its former major sponsor, sausage producer Steff-Houlberg. Fans from the away team are assigned a section on this stand, usually in the eastern part of the North Stand, separated from Br\u00f8ndby's home fans.\n\n=== West Stand ===\nThe West Stand, known as \"[[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg]]-tribunen\", was originally named \"Frisko-tribunen and later also \"SAS-tribunen\" and \"Apollo-tribunen\". The original part of the stand was completed in 1979 as the first stand of the stadium, and it has been preserved through the large expansion in 1999\u20132000. It can also accommodate a few fans in executive boxes and hospitality suites, and is the ground's main grandstand.\n\n=== East Stand ===\nThe East Stand, now known as \"GSV-tribunen\" for sponsorship reasons, was formerly called \"LOXAM-tribunen\", \"[[Codan]]-tribunen and \"DNE-tribunen\". The lower section of the stand was constructed in 1982 and 1990. The East Stand was originally without a roof, and consisted of terraces. Today, it is the largest stand of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion with a total of 34 rows of seats. In 2006, a larger extension was established behind the stand from the facade, consisting of sponsor facilities, a sports bar and classrooms for Br\u00f8ndby Gymnasium. The classrooms were inaugurated on 8 January 2007. In April 2018, a new family lounge was opened behind the East Stand with both physical and Esports facilities.\n\n==Transportation==\nThe easiest way of getting to the stadium with public transport is with the [[S-tog]] or S-train. Line B (green) will stop at both Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster and Glostrup stations, where there are shuttle buses on match days. One can also walk from the stations, with the walk taking 15 minutes from Glostrup, and slightly longer from Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster.\n\n==National games==\nBr\u00f8ndby Stadion has been used five times as home ground for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]]. Further it has been the venue of four youth national matches and a league national match:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dbu.dk/page.aspx?id=5641 |title=Landsholdsdatabasen |publisher=[[Danish Football Association]] |accessdate=2010-03-01 |language=Danish }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Home team\n!Res.\n!Away team\n!Competition\n!Spectators\n|-\n|11 September 1982||[[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20130||[[West Germany national under-19 football team|West Germany U-19]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|5 May 1984||[[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||[[East Germany national under-19 football team|East Germany U-19]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|19 November 1986||[[Denmark national under-17 football team|Denmark U-17]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20130||[[Cyprus national under-17 football team|Cyprus U-17]]||[[1987 UEFA European Under-16 Football Championship]] qualifying||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|6 March 2002||[[Denmark League XI national football team|Denmark League XI]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||[[Norway League XI national football team|Norway League XI]]||Non-official match||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|1 September 2006||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20132||[[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|13,186\n|-\n|19 November 2008||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||[[Wales national football team|Wales]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|10,271\n|-\n|12 August 2009||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20132||[[Chile national football team|Chile]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|8,700\n|-\n|30 May 2013||[[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20131||[[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany U-19]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1,060\n|-\n|6 June 2017||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||[[German national football team|Germany]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|15,488\n|-\n|22 March 2018||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20130||[[Panama national football team|Panama]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|11,150\n|-\n|7 June 2020||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|-||[[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{cite book |last1=Barnak |first1=S\u00f8ren |title=Br\u00f8ndby IF --fordi de ville! : Br\u00f8ndbyernes Idr\u00e6tsforening 1964-2004 |year=2004 |publisher=Br\u00f8nden |isbn=8790667042 |edition=1. udgave}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Laursen Brock |first1=Jeppe |title=Br\u00f8ndby IF : historien om drengene fra Vestegnen |date=2011 |publisher=Gyldendal |location=K\u00f8benhavn K |isbn=978-87-02-10258-1 |edition=1. udgave, 1. oplag}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Rasmussen |first1=Jens Jam |title=Formanden. Bind 1 : historien om Per Bjerregaard og Br\u00f8ndby IF |date=2009 |publisher=People'sPress |location=K\u00f8benhavn |isbn=978-87-7055-435-0 |edition=1. udgave}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Storm |first1=Rasmus K. |last2=Thomsen |first2=Frederik |title=For better or worse? A study of institutional responses to sports competitive pressure in Danish pro soccer 2001\u20132013 |edition= |pages= |journal=European Journal for Sport and Society |volume=13 |issue=4 |pp=274\u2013295 |doi=10.1080/16138171.2016.1248092}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060515075200/http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=84 Br\u00f8ndby Stadion]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120527153004/http://allstadiums.ru/evropa/stadiony-danii/brondby.html Br\u00f8ndby Stadion]\n\n{{commons|Br\u00f8ndby Stadion}}\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF}}\n{{Danish Superliga stadiumlist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brondby Stadion}}\n[[Category:Br\u00f8ndby IF]]\n[[Category:Football venues in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Br\u00f8ndby Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Danish|Br\u00f8ndby Stadion|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name      = Br\u00f8ndby Stadion\n| image             = Br\u00f8ndby stadium panorama.jpg\n| image_size        = 300px\n| caption           = Br\u00f8ndby Stadion in 2006\n| nickname          = [[Kim Vilfort|Vilfort]] Park<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hansen |first1=Niels O. |title=Br\u00f8ndby Stadion skal fremover hedde... |url=https://www.bt.dk/superligaen/broendby-stadion-skal-fremover-hedde |website=bt.dk |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=11 October 2016}}</ref><br />\"Hell in the [[Scandinavia|North]]\"<ref>{{cite web |title=10. etape 2008 |url=https://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/10-etape-2008/ |website=brondby.com |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n| location          = [[List of postal codes in Denmark#Zealand (1000-3699 and 4000-4999)|2605]] [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]],<br />[[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality]],<br />Denmark\n| coordinates       = {{coord|55|38|55.82|N|12|25|06.66|E|type:landmark_region:DK_scale:2000}}\n| broke_ground      =\n| publictransit = {{S-train service small|B}}{{S-train service small|Bx}} at [[Glostrup station|Glostrup]] or<br />{{S-train service small|B}} at [[Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster station|Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster]]\n| built             = 1965\n| opened            = 31 June 1966<ref name=\"Barnak3233\">Barnak 2007, pp. 28\u201329.</ref>\n| renovated         = 1999\u20132000\n| expanded          = 1978, 1982, 1989, 1992, 2007\n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] [[Aktieselskab|A/S]]\n| operator          = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]\n| surface           = [[GrassMaster]] hybrid grass\n| construction_cost = \n| architect         = KSH Arkitekt & Ingeni\u00f8r (1999\u20132000; renovation)<ref>{{cite web |title=Stadion & haller |url=http://arkitekt-ksh.dk/index.php/projekter/station-og-haller |website=arkitekt-ksh.dk |publisher=KSH Arkitekt & Ingeni\u00f8r |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| structural engineer =\n| services engineer =\n| general_contractor=\n| project_manager   =\n| main_contractors  = \n| former_names      = \n| tenants           = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] (1965\u2013) <br /> Br\u00f8ndby Atletik (1965\u20131991) <br /> [[Denmark national football team]] (selected matches)\n| seating_capacity  = 28,000<ref name=\"stadionoverblik\">{{cite web |title=Stadionoverblik |url=https://brondby.com/klub/stadion/stadionoverblik/ |website=brondby.com |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref> (23,400 seats)\n| record_attendance = 31,508 (v. [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]]; 18 June 2003)\n| suites              = 5<ref>{{cite web |title=Oversigt over faciliteter |url=https://event.brondby.com/faciliteter/ |website=event.brondby.com |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby Event |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n| dimensions        = {{convert|105|x|68|m|yd|abbr=on}}\n}}\n'''Br\u00f8ndby Stadion''' {{IPA-da|\u02c8p\u0281\u0276npy st\u025b\u02c8tj\u028cn|pron}} is a [[Association football|football]] [[stadium]] in [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]], Denmark and the home ground of [[Danish Superliga]] club [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]. It is the second largest stadium in [[Denmark]]. Built in 1965 and inaugurated on 31 June 1966 where it had no stands, it saw a major redevelopment in 2000 which increased capacity to 31,500 spectators, of which 19,700 were seated. Continuous adjustments to the spectator facilities have since resulted in the stadium having a total capacity of 28,000 spectators, of which 23,400 are seated. Record attendance dates to 18 June 2003, where a crowd of 31,508 were present in a [[Copenhagen Derby]] against [[F.C. Copenhagen]].\n\nWhen hosting the [[UEFA]] competitions [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]], seats are installed on the South End [[Terrace (stadium)|terraces]] ({{lang-da|Sydsiden}}) in accordance with UEFA regulations, which reduces the total capacity to 26,000.\n\nThe stadium has also hosted the [[Denmark national football team]] in five matches. Their first game at Br\u00f8ndby Stadion was a [[exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] on 1 September 2006 which ended in a 4\u20132 win.\n\n== History ==\n=== Turning idea into product ===\nThe idea of constructing a centrally located, municipal sports facility was presented by erstwhile mayor [[Jens Christian Jensen (mayor)|Jens Christian Jensen]] in 1945,<ref name=\"Barnak27\">Barnak 2007, p. 27.</ref> but at the time the sports clubs of the municipality could not agree on a common stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak27\"/> \n\nWhen a merger of the municipality's three largest sports clubs was considered in the 1950s, much suggests that these plans were fostered on a political as well as executive level.<ref name=\"Barnak27\"/> Having only one club in the municipality would enable a more rational use of a future Br\u00f8ndby Stadion.<ref name=\"Barnak27\"/> The idea of a merger gained support in [[Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Idr\u00e6tsforening]], and at the general assembly in 1962 a majority of the board voted their approval of merging [[:da:Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening|Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening]] and [[:da:Br\u00f8ndby Strands Idr\u00e6tsklub|Br\u00f8ndby Strands Idr\u00e6tsforeninger]].<ref name=\"Barnak28\"/> The latter, however, immediately disapproved of the idea, while a vote in Br\u00f8ndbyvester ended up with the same result: a 'no' to merging into a municipal superstructure.<ref name=\"Barnak28\">Barnak 2007, p. 28.</ref>\n\nOnly a few years would pass before plans of merging Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Idr\u00e6tsforening and Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening would resurface.<ref name=\"Barnak28\"/> Financial benefit was one of the main arguments for uniting the two clubs in order to play at a future municipal stadium,<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\">{{cite news |author= |title=Stadion till\u00e6g |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |pages= 2 |date=22 October 2000 }}</ref> and mayor of [[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality|Br\u00f8ndby]] in the period 1966\u20132005, as well as chairman of [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] board in 1971\u201371, [[Kjeld Rasmussen]], has since stated that he and Br\u00f8ndby's mayor at the time had decided to construct a stadium, provided that the two clubs would merge.<ref name=\"Barnak61\">Barnak 2007, p. 61.</ref> {{quotation|The closer we came to a completion of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion, the stronger grew the support of forming one big club. Its proponents saw obvious advantages in a merger, which would mean that administrative personnel and athletes would have better physical surroundings to exercise and compete, and finally it would benefit both horisontally and vertically that all energy would become gathered in one club. Eventually, it was suggested that a merger would mean avoiding a reciprocal competitiveness especially in the area of municipal subsidies||[[Kjeld Rasmussen (mayor)|Kjeld Rasmussen]], Mayor of Br\u00f8ndby Municipality, 1966\u20132005.<ref name=\"Barnak28\"/>}}\n\nOn 3 December 1964 in Kirkebjerg Salen in [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]], the boards of Br\u00f8ndbyvester Idr\u00e6tsforening and Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Idr\u00e6tsforening adopted an agreement to merge into one club: [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndbyernes Idr\u00e6tsforening]] (Br\u00f8ndby IF).<ref name=\"Rasmussen37\">Rasmussen 2009, pp. 37\u201338.</ref><ref name=\"64-70\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/historie/1970-1964/ |title=Br\u00f8ndby - 1964\u20131970 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n=== Construction and early years ===\nWhen the stadium reached its completion in 1965, the ground consisted of nothing more than a grass pitch surrounded by an [[sport of athletics|athletics]] track and a spectator rail circling the field of play, a training complex featuring four grass pitches, and a gravel pitch.<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\"/> Behind one of the goals various athletics facilities were established, as the club shared the stadium with Br\u00f8ndby Atletik.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=1. etape - 1965: Masser af luft |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/1-etape-1965/ |publisher=brondby.com |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> In addition, a changing room with four separate compartments was constructed, featuring showers and toilet facilities.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/><ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\"/> \n\nThe official inauguration of the pitch was officially planned for late Summer 1965, but issues with making the grass grow postponed the launch to 31 July 1966.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/>\n\nIn the following years, the area around Br\u00f8ndby Stadion continuously developed and expanded; in 1969\u201370 the municipality constructed additional training pitches South of the ground, close to the [[Danish national road 21|Holb\u00e6k Motorway]],<ref name=\"Barnak33\">Barnak 2007, p. 33</ref> and even more training complexes were built South of the motorway in 1972\u201374.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/>\n\nConditions around the main playing pitch were also improved; in 1966 two [[turnstile]]s were set up at the stadium entrance,<ref name=\"Barnak33\"/> and in 1969 a clock was added, courtesy of local [[watchmaker]] Bent Henriksen from [[Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster Torv]].<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/> In 1973 the municipality allocated [[Danish krone|DKK]] 20,000 to set up a modern loudspeaker system consisting of four ''folded'' [[horn loudspeaker]]s suspended on four-metre steel trusses.<ref name=\"Barnak3233\"/>\n\n=== Constructing the stands ===\nAs [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] moved up the ranks, a need arose for a more contemporary stadium. In 1975, the [[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality|municipality]] allowed the club to improve spectator facilities by installing two-step terraces around the [[running track]].<ref name=\"Barnak72\">Barnak 2007, p. 72</ref> This happened despite the club's wishes to install a covered grandstand.<ref name=\"Barnak72\"/>\n\nOnly in 1977, when the club reached promotion to the third highest football league in Denmark, the [[Danish 2nd Division]], did the municipality decide that a covered grandstand should be erected.<ref name=\"Barnak73\"/> The [[Danish krone|DKK]] 4 million project broke ground during the summer of 1978, and in early 1979 the grandstand was ready for use.<ref name=\"Barnak73\">Barnak 2007, p. 73</ref> The stand, which could hold 1,335 seated spectators, and included a [[announcer|speaker]] booth, media facilities and a TV plateau, was placed facing West towards [[Gildh\u00f8j (Br\u00f8ndby Municipality)|Gildh\u00f8jskolen]].<ref name=\"Barnak73\"/> Beneath the stand were constructed four dressing rooms, a kiosk, an office, toilet facilities, a storage room as well as the club room of Br\u00f8ndby Atletik.<ref name=\"Barnak73\"/> In the spring of 1980, the municipality installed the first floodlights with a brightness of 4 x 24&nbsp;kW.<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg\"/> With the new stand, spectator capacity increased to 5,000.<ref name=\"Barnak72\"/>\n\nAs Br\u00f8ndby IF had reached promotion to the highest football league in Denmark in the fall of 1981, then known as the [[Danish Superliga|1st Division]], mayor Kjeld Rasmussen proclaimed that a covered stand would be constructed.<ref name=\"Barnak80\">Barnak 2007, p. 80</ref> Prior to the [[1982 Danish 1st Division|1982 season]] &ndash; Br\u00f8ndby's first on the highest level &ndash; concrete [[Terrace (stadium)|terraces]] were installed opposite the existing grandstand, consisting of 13 rows of terraces the length of the pitch in open air.<ref name=\"Stadion tillaeg2\">{{cite news |author= |title=Stadion till\u00e6g |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |date=22 October 2000 }}</ref> This allowed a crowd of 5,000 additional people,<ref name=\"3. etape\">{{cite news |author= |title=3. etape - 1982: St\u00e5pladser til folket |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/3-etape-1982/ |publisher=brondby.com |pages= |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> bringing the total capacity to 10,000.\n\n[[File:Br\u00f8ndby_Stadion_2005-04.jpg|thumb|left|Br\u00f8ndby Stadion as seen from the South in 2005.]]\nAfter the club had established itself in the top of [[Football in Denmark|Danish football]] during the 1980s, Br\u00f8ndby IF reached a hitherto zenith by reaching the [[1990\u201391_UEFA_Cup#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]] of the [[1990\u201391 UEFA Cup]].<ref name=\"FiB07\">{{cite web|url=https://brondby.com/nyhed/2007/03/20/fra-mark-til-arena|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=Fra mark til Arena|date=20 March 2007|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Rasmussen205207\">Rasmussen 2009, pp. 205\u2013207.</ref> At that time, Br\u00f8ndby Stadion did not live up to international standards to host matches at that level. However, this was solved by installing temporary end stands of [[scaffolding]], which allowed the club to receive an approval by the [[UEFA]] to organise the home leg against [[FC Torpedo Moscow|Torpedo Moscow]].<ref name=\"FiB07\"/> The changes raised the total capacity to 15,000 spectators, and the club even outdid themselves when they reached the [[1990\u201391_UEFA_Cup#Semi-finals|semi-finals]] by increasing the capacity to 17,000&ndash;18,000.<ref>{{cite news |author= |title=5. etape - 1991: Den usl\u00e5elige stadionrekord |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/4-etape-1989/ |publisher=brondby.com |pages= |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref> In the same period Br\u00f8ndby IF submitted a bid to host the [[Denmark national football team]] at a new national stadium; a \"''Stadion Danmark''\", which would seat 60,000 spectators and border the [[Danish national road 21|Holb\u00e6k Motorway]].<ref name=\"FiB07\" /> These plans, however, never came to fruition as [[Parken Stadium]] won the bid and eventually became the national stadium.<ref>{{cite web |title=Parken, Danmarks Nationalstadion |url=https://www.cfmoller.com/p/-da/Parken-Danmarks-Nationalstadion-i34.html# |website=cfmoller.com |publisher=[[C. F. M\u00f8ller Architects]] |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs Br\u00f8ndby IF gained domestic and European success, spectator interest had grown to such a degree, that it became necessary to move the biggest matches to [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]].<ref name=\"4. etape\">{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415020824/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=77 |title=4. etape - 1989-1990 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |date=1 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415020824/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=77 |archivedate=15 August 2012 |accessdate=10 April 2020 }}</ref> This solution was not deemed satisfactory for neither club, fans nor sponsors, who wanted to remain rooted in the local community.<ref name=\"4. etape\"/><ref name=\"FiB07\"/> Therefore, the board under leadership of [[Per Bjerregaard]], decided to plan an expansion of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\">Barnak 2007, pp. 139-140</ref> The first step was taken in 1990, when the stand opposite the grandstand was covered and expanded with eight rows, holding 3,500 seated spectators, as well as terracing holding 10,500 standing spectators in total.<ref name=\"BT 1991-03-12\">{{cite news |title=B.T. tester de 10 Superliga stadion |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=12 March 1991 |page=2 }}</ref> In the same year the grandstand was expanded with a lounge for sponsors in which a panoramic window allowed for a view of the entire pitch.<ref name=\"FiB07\"/> While Br\u00f8ndby Municipality had financed the new covered stand, Br\u00f8ndby IF funded the construction of the sponsors lounge.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/>\n\nDespite improved spectator facilities, the stadium did still not live up to UEFA requirements,<ref name=\"6. etape\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/6-etape-1992/ |title=6. etape - 1992 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> and the club wished to erect permanent terracing behind both goals.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> As this would mean that the running track around the pitch had to be demolished, and that Br\u00f8ndby Atletik would have to be compensated with a new running track elsewhere,<ref name=\"BT-1991-06-12\">{{cite news |last=Fredberg |first=Peter |title=Vi ofrer ikke atletikken |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=12 June 1991 |page=34 }}</ref> the municipality chose to turn down Br\u00f8ndby IF's application to further expand the stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\">Barnak 2007, pp. 139-140</ref> This made the club consider moving to another city where it would be able to host international games,<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> prompting the municipality to offer Br\u00f8ndby IF to acquire the stadium and thus raise money to construct an athletics stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> The club board, spearheaded by Bjerregaard, was, however, only interested in purchasing the area behind the two goals.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/> Br\u00f8ndby IF had meanwhile offered to pay for construction costs of the end stands themselves, but in order to do so the pitch had to be expanded both in width and length.<ref name=\"Barnak139140\"/>\n\nIn 1991, the municipal council decided that Br\u00f8ndby IF should have the sole right to use the stadium.<ref name=\"Barnak140141\">Barnak 2007, pp. 140-141</ref> Thus, a green light was finally given to turn Br\u00f8ndby Stadion into a [[Soccer-specific stadium|football-specific stadium]]. In December 1991, the contractor began removing the running track,<ref name=\"Barnak140141\"/> and in the spring of 1992, the expanded Br\u00f8ndby Stadion has reached completion: four covered stands with a total capacity of almost 21,000 spectators.<ref name=\"BT 1991-02-13\">{{cite news |last=Fredberg |first=Peter |title=Nu f\u00e5r Br\u00f8ndby sit Super-Stadion |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid|B.T.]] |date=13 February 1991 |page=33 }}</ref><ref name=\"BT 1991-08-07\">{{cite news |last=Uno |first=Steeb |title=Br\u00f8ndby f\u00e5r sit EC-stadion |work=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=7 August 1991 |page=28 }}</ref> This included the infamous terraced \"South Side\"-end ({{lang-da|Sydsiden}}) &ndash; then known as ''[[Faxe Brewery|Faxe]] Tribunen'' for sponsorship reasons &ndash; which was inaugurated on 29 March 1992.<ref name=\"6. etape\"/> With the 1,335 seats on the main grandstand and another 3,000 new seats on the lower side of the opposite stand, the stadium could hold more than 6,000 seated spectators.<ref name=\"Barnak141\">Barnak 2007, p. 141</ref>\n\n=== 1999\u20132000 expansion ===\nDespite several expansions and improvements over the years, Br\u00f8ndby Stadion could still not achieve acceptable capacity for international matches, and the club was therefore forced to rent [[Parken Stadium]] in [[Indre \u00d8sterbro]] &ndash; home of the [[Denmark national football team|national team]] as well as archrivals [[F.C. Copenhagen|FC Copenhagen]] &ndash; for major matches under [[UEFA]].<ref name=\"6. etape\"/> This resulted in losses; both on a financial level, but also in terms of prestige, and because of this the board continued to work on plans of further expanding the stadium.<ref name=\"6. etape\"/>\n\nThe first step was commencing negotiations with [[Br\u00f8ndby Municipality]] in order to secure the total acquisition of the stadium, and as a result of the proceedings, [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] [[Aktieselskab|A/S]] purchased Br\u00f8ndby Stadion for [[Danish krone|DKK]] 23.5 million in May 1998.<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-05-14\">{{cite news |title=Br\u00f8ndby k\u00f8ber eget stadion for 23,5 mio - BIF |work=[[Reuters]] |date=14 May 1998 }}</ref><ref>Storm & Thomsen 2016, p. 278</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Larsen |first1=Christian W. |title=Br\u00f8ndby f\u00e5r eget stadion |publisher=[[Aktuelt]] |date=14 May 1998}}</ref> From this, DKK 16 million was to be deducted for the two end stands and the sponsors lounge,<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-05-14\"/> which the club itself had financed, resulting in a final amount of DKK 7.3 million.<ref name=\"Barnak180\">Barnak 2007, p. 180</ref>\n\nThe acquisition officially took place on 1 January 1999,<ref name=\"Barnak180\"/> after which the largest expansion of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion could commence;<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-11-02\">{{cite news |title=Kapitaludvidelse i Br\u00f8ndby 2 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2 November 1998 }}</ref> a connected upper stand supported by a total of 32 concrete [[Staircase tower|staircase towers]],<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> and a new roof carried by a total of 32 m tall iron structures, each 25 m apart.<ref name=\"Barnak180\"/> These would &ndash; together with the existing lower stands &ndash; ensure that the stadium could bring the total spectator capacity to more than 30,000 for [[UEFA|European games]] and 33,000 to [[Danish Superliga|domestic]] matches.<ref name=\"Reuters 1998-10-19\">{{cite news |title=Nyt stadion \u00f8ger Br\u00f8ndby-res 15-20 mio - prospekt |work=[[Reuters]] |date=19 October 1998 }}</ref> The total costs for the expansion were DKK 270 million,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_069yfp0l4ln18ma686z5_34271.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2000|pages=10-11|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> 40 million more than original estimates due to costs spiralling.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_wumjjipadudjnqgt2xau_34260.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2001|page=9 }}</ref> In addition to the new upper stand section, the main grandstand was expanded with a superstructure.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pedersen|first=Flemming|title=Ny tribune st\u00e5r klar til n\u00e6ste \u00e5r|date=2 September 1998|publisher=Politiken, section 1 page 19}}</ref> Not least, the sponsor and lounge areas were expanded considerably,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> and a new three-storey annex providing administrative offices, press facilities, commercial kitchen and lounge areas able to host more than 3,000 was erected facing the parking lot.<ref name=\"Barnak181\">Barnak 2007, p. 181</ref> On the ground floor were constructed additional facilies, including a lobby, a gym for the players and a fanshop.<ref name=\"Barnak181\"/>\n[[File:Br\u00f8ndby_Stadion.JPG|thumb|right|Aerial view of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion.]]\n\nThe connected upper stands meant that the corners of the stadium became partly enclosed, and toilet stalls as well as food and drink outlets were placed in the spaces between the lower and upper stands.<ref name=\"Barnak181\"/> The new upper stands included 13,600 new seats, increasing the total capacity to 31,500 spectators.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> For international matches, capacity was limited to 26,500 spectators as they demand [[all-seater|all-seated]] crowds.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> The entire redevelopment was carried out while the club still played its home games at the stadium, and the original changing rooms under the main grandstand, originating from 1978, were retained.<ref name=\"Barnak181\"/>\n\nThe stadium officially reopened with a ceremony on 22 October 2000,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> followed by an [[exhibition game]] between the [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] team from 1989 and [[:da:Skagen Idr\u00e6ts Klub|Skagen IK]]; a rematch mirroring a [[1986\u201387 Danish Cup]] game, where Skagen from the Danish fifth tier knocked out Br\u00f8ndby after a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty-shootout]], in what has been described as \"the biggest sensation in Danish Cup history\".<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Videb\u00e6k |first1=Klaus |title=Da Skagen IK slog Br\u00f8ndby: 'Det st\u00f8rste jeg har oplevet i mit sportsliv' |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/regionale/nordjylland/da-skagen-ik-slog-broendby-det-stoerste-jeg-har-oplevet-i-mit |website=dr.dk |publisher=[[Danmarks Radio]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=27 April 2017}}</ref> The first competitive game after the rebuild occurred on 22 October 2000 with a 4&ndash;2 league win over [[Akademisk Boldklub]] in front of 28,416 spectators.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rachlin |first1=Michael |title=Br\u00f8ndbys dejlige dag |url=https://jyllands-posten.dk/indland/kbh/ECE3300722/Br%C3%B8ndbys-dejlige-dag/ |website=jyllands-posten.dk |publisher=[[Jyllands-Posten]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=22 October 2000}}</ref> \n\nThe stadium reached total completion in 2001.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2000\"/> The redevelopment also made Br\u00f8ndby Stadion a part of the Nordic countries' [[UEFA Euro 2008 bids|bid]] for hosting the [[UEFA Euro 2008]], which was eventually awarded to [[Austria]]\u2013[[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Austria-Switzerland to host Euro 2008 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/2569017.stm |website=bbc.co.uk/sport |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=12 December 2002}}</ref>\n\n=== Additions and improvements ===\nBecause the total costs of the 1999\u20132000 expansion exceeded the originally planned budget by [[Danish krone|DKK]] 30\u201340 million, some major and minor additions and improvements to audience facilities were postponed and subsequently carried out over time.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2001\"/><ref name=\"Barnak181\"/> First of foremost, the club could not afford new turnstiles, and a planned, highly modern entrance system was only installed in 2003, just as the scoreboards initally did not meet the requirements of the [[Danish Football Union]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apps.infomedia.dk/mediearkiv/link?articles=e008d0b4 |title=11 superligastadions dumpet |publisher=[[Ritzau]] |date=30 June 2003 |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> The original substitutes' benches in the [[technical area]] likewise had to be utilised for some years before being permanently replaced by benches below pitch-level in 2005.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_vrizkpoxn3iharmmlzhm_36880.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2005|accessdate=17January 2015|page=19}}</ref>\n\nThe new blue seats planned for the lower stands would initially have to wait; firstly, the old, worn-out seats were retained on the two original longside stands, which in the first years following the rebuild appeared as gray, red, yellow and light blue seats. Secondly, seats were expected to be fitted to the extended section of the old grandstand and the lower section of the northern end stand. However, an extra \"row 34\" was added relatively quickly all the way around the top of the stands, in front of the glass partitions.\n\nAs new dark blue seats were installed on the aforementioned areas in 2003, a total seating capacity reached 23,400. This increased total stadium capacity to 29,000,<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2003\">{{cite web|url=http://brondby.com/upload/biffile_vrj7ojvt3bb7yet69qvf_34266.pdf|publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]|title=\u00c5rsrapport 2003|accessdate=17 January 2015|page=11}}</ref> while the stadium could hold crowds of 26,144 for international matches.<ref name=\"\u00c5rsrapport 2003\"/> This was due to the fact that for international fixtures, the South Side-end [[Terrace (stadium)|terracing]] could be converted into approximately 2,600 seats.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lassen |first1=Kurt |title=St\u00e5drengene fra Vestegnen |url=https://www.berlingske.dk/sport/staadrengene-fra-vestegnen |website=berlingske.dk |publisher=[[Berlingske]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=13 March 2004}}</ref> Despite many delayed improvements to the stadium, the redevelopment in 2000 already had already secured improved facilities for wheelchair users, as a wheelchair lift had been installed at the southern end of the East Stand.<ref name=\"stadionoverblik\" />\n\nIn 2006\u20132007, the East Stand (today known as ''GSV Stand'' ({{lang-da|GSV-tribunen}}) for sponsorship reasons) was further expanded at the back with a lounge for sponsors, classrooms for [[:da:Br\u00f8ndby Gymnasium|Br\u00f8ndby Gymnasium]] ([[Secondary education in Denmark|general upper secondary education]]), a public gym, a production kitchen and the sports bar \"''1964''\".<ref name=\"RB B\u00f8rsen 2006-03-07\">{{cite news |title=Br\u00f8ndby opf\u00f8rer ny bygning p\u00e5 Br\u00f8ndby Stadion for 90 mio (Opd) |publisher=[[B\u00f8rsen]] |date=7 March 2006 }}</ref><ref name=\"9. etape\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/9-etape-2007/ |title=9. etape - 2007 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 }}</ref> In addition, spectator conditions were improved upon with six new multi-stalls and three new staircases beneath the East Stand.<ref name=\"9. etape\"/> Two large [[Light-emitting diodes|LED]] screens were also installed during this period.<ref name=\"9. etape\"/> The total cost of the project ran up to DKK 90 million.<ref name=\"RB B\u00f8rsen 2006-03-07\"/>\n\nIn 2008, major sponsor [[:da:Jesper Laustrup Nielsen|Jesper \"Kasi-Jesper\" Nielsen]] of [[:da:KasiGroup|KasiGroup]] financed a decoration of the Br\u00f8ndby Stadion facade;<ref name=\"BT 2014-12-03\">{{cite news |last=Holm |first=Emil Broo |title=Gaver til f\u00f8dselaren: Det har Br\u00f8ndby modtaget gennem tiden |publisher=[[B.T. (tabloid)|B.T.]] |date=3 December 2014 }}</ref> yellow, illuminated letters with the stadium name affixed between the roof and the top row of seating at three of the stands.<ref name=\"10. etape\">{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/klub/stadion/historie/10-etape-2008/ |title=10. etape - 2008 |publisher=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] |accessdate=8 December 2012 }}</ref> In addition, each [[gable]] was adorned with four large images that showed [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] players and fans in different situations.<ref name=\"10. etape\"/>\n\nDuring the winter break in of the [[2017\u201318 Br\u00f8ndby IF season|2017\u201318 season]], the hole on the South Side-end was closed which meant that an additional 75 seats and extra capacity for 150 standing spectators on terracing were added to the stadium.<ref name=\"TipsSyd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tipsbladet.dk/nyhed/superliga/broendby-fans-betaler-selv-ombygning-af-sydsiden|title=Br\u00f8ndby-fans betaler selv ombygningen af Sydsiden|work=[[Tipsbladet]]|date=22 December 2017|accessdate=23 April 2018|author=Lasse Sylvest Mikkelsen}}</ref> The rebuild was financed by the club's fans, through the official fanclub ''[[Br\u00f8ndby_IF#Support|Br\u00f8ndby Support]]'' and various unofficial fan groups,<ref name=\"TipsSyd\"/> and through a so-called \"fan fund\" which arose as a result of season tickets and merchandise sales, among other things.<ref name=\"VaerMed\">{{cite web|url=https://brondby.com/nyhed/2017/12/13/vaer-med-til-at-forbedre-sydsiden|title=V\u00e6r med til at forbedre Sydsiden|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=23 April 2018|work=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]}}</ref> In total, the renovation costs amounted to DKK 450,000, of which the fan fund accounted for DKK 270,000.<ref name=\"TipsSyd\"/><ref name=\"VaerMed\"/> In the summer of 2018, new 256 LED floodlights were installed, produced in China.<ref name=\"Lys2018\">{{cite web|url=https://brondby.com/nyhed/2018/07/10/454399|title=Nyt lys skal langtidssikre Br\u00f8ndby Stadion|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=11 July 2018|work=[[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]}}</ref>\n\n== Structure and facilities ==\nThe Br\u00f8ndby Stadion pitch is surrounded by four covered stands, officially known as Sydsiden (South), GSV-tribunen (East), J. Jensen-tribunen (North) and Carlsberg-tribunen (West). Three stands are all-seaters (except the away section on the North End) while the South End is terracing. Each stand has two tiers.\n\n=== Sydsiden (South End) ===\nSydsiden, literally \"South Side\" in English, was inaugurated as the new South Stand on 29 March 1992 in a match against [[Lyngby Boldklub]], due to a rise in interest for Br\u00f8ndby IF.<ref name=\"FiB07\"/><ref name=Sydsiden2>{{cite web |url=https://sydsiden.brondby.com/ |title=Sydsiden 25 \u00e5r |date=15 March 2017 |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |accessdate=15 March}}</ref> The lower part of the stand has a standing capacity of 5,600 spectators. Initially, spectators would sit on the terraces,<ref name=Sydsiden>{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/nyhed/2017/03/14/de-foerste-aar-paa-sydsiden |title=De F\u00f8rste \u00c5r P\u00e5 Sydsiden |date=15 March 2017 |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> but younger fans would begin encouraging all fans on Sydsiden to stand up, because they thought that it was easier to sing while standing, which would evolve into the mantra \"sing or piss off\" ({{lang-da|syng eller skrid}}).<ref name=Sydsiden/> This would mark the beginning of a hard-core fan-culture formation on Sydsiden, which has remained ever since, and it is known as the stand in Denmark with the most dedicated and loudest fans when Br\u00f8ndby plays its home games.<ref name=\"6. etape\"/>\n\nUntil 6 March 2011, Sydsiden was known by its sponsor name, \"Faxe Tribunen\", a subsidiary of [[Royal Unibrew]]. This had to change as there was a conflict of interest as [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg]] moved in as new sponsors. Sydsiden was chosen by a panel representing a broad section of the active fan base at Br\u00f8ndby Stadion, as fans had called the stand this before.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brondby.com/nyhed/2011/01/18/faxe-tribunen-bliver-til-sydsiden |title=Faxe-tribunen bliver til Sydsiden |date=18 January 2011 |publisher=Br\u00f8ndby IF |accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> Halfway through the 2017\u201318 season, the hole in the middle of the stand was partly closed, after continuous requests by fans.<ref name=\"VaerMed\"/>\n\nA permanent fanzone was inaugurated outside Sydsiden in 2018 for spectators and fans before, during and after the games. The fanzone is the first of its kind in Scandinavia, and consists of stands for live concerts, bars, foodstands and toilet facilities.\n\nSydsiden popularised the \"Fenerbah\u00e7e greeting\" in Denmark, imported through the transfer of [[Brian Steen Nielsen]] to the Turkish club. A cooperation between goalkeeper [[Mogens Krogh]] and [[Br\u00f8ndby IF#Support|Br\u00f8ndby Support]] effectually made the greeting get foothold in Denmark.<ref name=Sydsiden/>\n\n=== North End ===\nThe North Stand, now known as \"J. Jensen-tribunen\" for sponsorship reasons, was originally known as \"da:OBS!-tribunen\". The lower section of the stand was constructed in 1992 as terracing, and has among fans been known as \"P\u00f8lseenden\" ({{lang-da|[[:da:Rosinen i p\u00f8lseenden|the sausage end]]}}) due to its former major sponsor, sausage producer Steff-Houlberg. Fans from the away team are assigned a section on this stand, usually in the eastern part of the North Stand, seperated from Br\u00f8ndby's home fans.\n\n=== West Stand ===\nThe West Stand, known as \"[[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg]]-tribunen\", was originally named \"Frisko-tribunen and later also \"SAS-tribunen\" and \"Apollo-tribunen\". The original part of the stand was completed in 1979 as the first stand of the stadium, and it has been preserved through the large expansion in 1999\u20132000. It can also accommodate a few fans in executive boxes and hospitality suites, and is the ground's main grandstand.\n\n=== East Stand ===\nThe East Stand, now known as \"GSV-tribunen\" for sponsorship reasons, was formerly called \"LOXAM-tribunen\", \"[[Codan]]-tribunen and \"DNE-tribunen\". The lower section of the stand was constructed in 1982 and 1990. The East Stand was originally without a roof, and consisted of terraces. Today, it is the largest stand of Br\u00f8ndby Stadion with a total of 34 rows of seats. In 2006, a larger extension was established behind the stand from the facade, consisting of sponsor facilities, a sports bar and classrooms for Br\u00f8ndby Gymnasium. The classrooms were inaugurated on 8 January 2007. In April 2018, a new family lounge was opened behind the East Stand with both physical and Esports facilities.\n\n==Transportation==\nThe easiest way of getting to the stadium with public transport is with the [[S-tog]] or S-train. Line B (green) will stop at both Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster and Glostrup stations, where there are shuttle buses on match days. One can also walk from the stations, with the walk taking 15 minutes from Glostrup, and slightly longer from Br\u00f8ndby\u00f8ster.\n\n==National games==\nBr\u00f8ndby Stadion has been used five times as home ground for the [[Denmark national football team|Danish national team]]. Further it has been the venue of four youth national matches and a league national match:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dbu.dk/page.aspx?id=5641 |title=Landsholdsdatabasen |publisher=[[Danish Football Association]] |accessdate=2010-03-01 |language=Danish }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Home team\n!Res.\n!Away team\n!Competition\n!Spectators\n|-\n|11 September 1982||[[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20130||[[West Germany national under-19 football team|West Germany U-19]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|5 May 1984||[[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||[[East Germany national under-19 football team|East Germany U-19]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|19 November 1986||[[Denmark national under-17 football team|Denmark U-17]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20130||[[Cyprus national under-17 football team|Cyprus U-17]]||[[1987 UEFA European Under-16 Football Championship]] qualifying||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|6 March 2002||[[Denmark League XI national football team|Denmark League XI]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||[[Norway League XI national football team|Norway League XI]]||Non-official match||style=\"text-align:center;\"|?\n|-\n|1 September 2006||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20132||[[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|13,186\n|-\n|19 November 2008||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131||[[Wales national football team|Wales]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|10,271\n|-\n|12 August 2009||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20132||[[Chile national football team|Chile]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|8,700\n|-\n|30 May 2013||[[Denmark national under-19 football team|Denmark U-19]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20131||[[Germany national under-19 football team|Germany U-19]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1,060\n|-\n|6 June 2017||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||[[German national football team|Germany]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|15,488\n|-\n|22 March 2018||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20130||[[Panama national football team|Panama]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|11,150\n|-\n|7 June 2020||[[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|-||[[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]||[[Friendly match]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{cite book |last1=Barnak |first1=S\u00f8ren |title=Br\u00f8ndby IF --fordi de ville! : Br\u00f8ndbyernes Idr\u00e6tsforening 1964-2004 |year=2004 |publisher=Br\u00f8nden |isbn=8790667042 |edition=1. udgave}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Laursen Brock |first1=Jeppe |title=Br\u00f8ndby IF : historien om drengene fra Vestegnen |date=2011 |publisher=Gyldendal |location=K\u00f8benhavn K |isbn=978-87-02-10258-1 |edition=1. udgave, 1. oplag}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Rasmussen |first1=Jens Jam |title=Formanden. Bind 1 : historien om Per Bjerregaard og Br\u00f8ndby IF |date=2009 |publisher=People'sPress |location=K\u00f8benhavn |isbn=978-87-7055-435-0 |edition=1. udgave}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Storm |first1=Rasmus K. |last2=Thomsen |first2=Frederik |title=For better or worse? A study of institutional responses to sports competitive pressure in Danish pro soccer 2001\u20132013 |edition= |pages= |journal=European Journal for Sport and Society |volume=13 |issue=4 |pp=274\u2013295 |doi=10.1080/16138171.2016.1248092}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060515075200/http://www.brondby.com/article.asp?aid=84 Br\u00f8ndby Stadion]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120527153004/http://allstadiums.ru/evropa/stadiony-danii/brondby.html Br\u00f8ndby Stadion]\n\n{{commons|Br\u00f8ndby Stadion}}\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF}}\n{{Danish Superliga stadiumlist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brondby Stadion}}\n[[Category:Br\u00f8ndby IF]]\n[[Category:Football venues in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Br\u00f8ndby Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Br%C3%B8ndby_Stadion"}
{"title_page": "Hunza Valley", "text_new": "{{For|the article about the former princely state|Hunza (princely state)}}\n{{original research|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name               = Hunza Valley\n| other_name         = \n| native_name        = \u06c1\u0646\u0632\u0648\n| native_name_lang   = bsk\n| translation        = \n| photo              = File:Rakaposhi, Nagar GB (Pakistan).jpg\n| photo_caption      = The {{Convert|7788|m}} tall [[Rakaposhi]] mountain towers over Hunza\n<!--    MAP     -->\n| map                = Gilgit Baltistan#Pakistan\n| map_image          = \n| map_caption        = \n<!--  Location  -->\n| location           = \n| country            = {{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]\n| region             = {{flagicon|Gilgit-Baltistan}} [[Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n| state              = \n| district           = [[Hunza District]]\n| city               = \n| relief             = \n| label              = \n| label_position     = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|36.316942|N|74.649900|E|display=inline}} \n| coordinates_ref    = <ref>{{cite web |title=Hunza on Google Maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hunza+Valley/ |website=Google Maps |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Statistics -->  \n| elevation          = \n| elevation_m        = \n| elevation_ft       = \n| elevation_ref      = \n| length             = \n| length_mi          = \n| length_km          = \n| length_orientation = \n| length_note        = \n| width              = \n| width_mi           = \n| width_km           = \n| width_orientation  = \n| width_note         = \n| area               = \n| area_mi2           = \n| area_km2           = \n| depth              = \n| depth_ft           = \n| depth_m            = \n| type               = \n| age                = \n| border             = \n| topo               = \n| traversed          = \n| river              = \n<!-- Below --> \n| footnotes          = \n| embed              = \n}}\n'''Hunza''' ({{lang-bsk|\u06c1\u0646\u0632\u0648}}, [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]]: \"{{lang|wbl|shina}}\", {{lang-ur|{{nq|\u06c1\u0646\u0632\u06c1}}}}) is a mountainous valley in the [[Gilgit-Baltistan|Gilgit-Baltistan region]] of [[Pakistan]]. Hunza is situated in the extreme northern part of Pakistan, bordering with the [[Wakhan Corridor]] of [[Afghanistan]] and the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang region]] of [[China]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mountainous Valley situated in extreme northern part of Pakistan |url=https://www.dreamstime.com/hunza-mountainous-valley-gilgit-baltistan-region-pakistan-hunza-situated-extreme-northern-part-image107691385 |website=www.dreamstime.com |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Hunza valley is situated at an elevation of 2,438 meters (7,999 feet).  Geographicaly, Hunza consists of three regions, Upper Hunza ([[Gojal]]), Central Hunza (\"Hunza Valley\") and Lower Hunza (\"Shinaki\"). \n\n== History ==\n{{main|State of Hunza}}\n[[File: Baltit Fort, Karimabad, Hunza, Gilgit Baltistan.jpg|thumb|[[Baltit Fort]], the former residence of the Mirs of Hunza]]\nHunza was formerly a [[princely state]] bordering  [[Xinjiang]] (autonomous region of China) to the northeast and [[Pamir Mountains|Pamir]] to the northwest, which survived until 1974, when it was finally dissolved by [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]].  The state bordered the [[Gilgit Agency]] to the south and the former princely state of [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]] to the east. The state capital was the town of Baltit (also known as [[Karimabad (Hunza)|Karimabad]]); another old settlement is [[Ganish Village]] which means \"ancient gold\" village. Hunza was an independent principality for more than 900 years until the [[British Raj|British]] gained control of it and the neighboring valley of Nagar between 1889 and 1891 through military conquest. The then [[Tham (title)|Mir/Tham]] (ruler), branch of [[Katoor Dynasty|Katur Dynasty]], Safdar Khan of Hunza fled to [[Kashghar]] in China and sought what would now be called political asylum.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Valley|first1=Hunza|title=Hunza Valley|url=http://www.skardu.pk/hunza-valley/|website=www.skardu.pk|publisher=Skardu.pk|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mir/Tham===\n{{main|Mir of Hunza}}\n\nAn account wrote by John Biddulph in his book ''[[Tribes of the Hindoo Koosh]]'' {{cquote|The ruling family of Hunza is called Ayesha (heavenly). The two states of [[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]] and [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]] were formerly one, ruled by a branch of the Shahreis, the ruling family of [[Gilgit]], whose seat of government was Nager. First muslim came to Hunza-Nagar Valley some 1000 years (At the time of Imam Isl\u0101m Sh\u0101h 30th Imam Ismaili Muslims). After the introduction of [[Islam]] to Gilgit, married a daughter of Trakhan of [[Gilgit]], who bore him twin sons, named Moghlot and Girkis. From the former, the present ruling family of Nager is descended. The twins are said to have shown hostility to one another from birth. Thereupon their father, unable to settle the question of succession, divided his state between them, giving Girkis the north/west, and to Moghlot the south/east bank of the river.<ref>Tribes of the Hindoo Koosh by John Biddulph page 26</ref>}}\n\n===2010 landslide===\nIn 2010, a landslide blocked the river and created [[Attabad Lake]] (also called shishket Lake), resulting in 20 deaths and 8 injuries and has effectively blocked about {{convert|26|km}} of the [[Karakoram Highway]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waheed |first1=Abdul |title=The Attabad Landslide Disaster |url=https://pamirtimes.net/2013/01/04/the-attabad-landslide-disaster/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |publisher=Pamir Times |date=4 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SHISHKET LAKE CRISES \u2013 2010 \u2013 CHRONOLOGY OF EVENTS |url=http://www.ndma.gov.pk/new/aboutus/SHISHKET_lake_2010.pdf |website=ndma.gov.pk |publisher=[[National Disaster Management Authority (Pakistan)|NDMA]] |accessdate=12 October 2019 |date=27 July 2010}}</ref> The new lake extends {{convert|30|km|mi}} and rose to a depth of {{convert|400|ft|m}} when it was formed as the Hunza River backed up.<ref name=\"fourworlds_HiMaT_2013\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fourworlds.ca/documents/ASecondGreenRevolution.pdf | title=Needed: a second green revolution in Hunza | publisher=HiMaT | date=May 2013 | accessdate=26 November 2015 | pages=4 | author1=Michael Bopp | author2=Judie Bopp}} Karakorum Area Development Organization (KADO), Aliabad</ref> The landslide completely covered sections of the Karakoram Highway.<ref name=\"fourworlds_HiMaT_2013\" />\n\n===2018 Rescue mission===\n[[File:Hunza Tunnel.jpg|thumb|right|Tunnel]]\nOn 1 July 2018, [[Pakistan Army]] pilots in a daring mission rescued 3 foreign mountaineers stuck in snow avalanche at above the height of {{Convert|19000|ft}} on [[Ultar Sar|Ultar Sar Peak]] near Hunza. The perilous weather conditions had made it difficult for the Army helicopter to go forth with a rescue operation on the {{Convert|7,388|m}} high [[Ultar Sar]]. But they completed it. Bruce Normand and Timothy Miller from [[United Kingdom|UK]] successfully rescued alive while their companion Christian Huber from [[Austria]] had succumbed to avalanche.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pakistan Army Pilots rescued 3 foreign mountaineers |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/headline/pakistan-army-rescues-avalanche-stricken-british-mountaineers-in-hunza-valley/ |website=en.dailypakistan.com.pk |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mountainers News on Thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/336019-pakistan-army-rescues-two-british-mountaineers-stranded-on |website=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nBritain's High Commissioner [[Thomas Drew (diplomat)|Thomas Drew]] in [[Pakistan]] termed the mission \u201cremarkable and dangerous\u201d and said:\n\n\u201c''Our gratitude to the [[Pakistan Army]] pilots who rescued two British climbers trapped by an avalanche on [[Ultar Sar|Ultar Sar Peak]] near Hunza. Our thoughts with their Austrian fellow climber who died\u201d''.\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Britain's High Commissioner in Pakistan admired Pak Army Pilots for rescued the two British Climbers |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/07/01/british-mountaineers-rescued-deadly-pakistan-avalanche-19000ft/ |website=www.telegraph.co.uk |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Major General Asif Ghafoor also tweeted about it |url=https://www.forces.net/news/british-climbers-rescued-pakistan-army |website=www.forces.net |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== People ==\n{{main|Hunza people}}\nThe local languages spoken include [[Burushaski]], [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]] and [[Shina language|Shina]]. The literacy rate of the Hunza valley is more than 95%.<ref name=\"education dawn\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.dawn.com/archives/29975|title=Hunza disaster and schools|first=Shahid|last=Siddiqui|work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> The historical area of Hunza and present northern Pakistan has had, over the centuries, mass migrations, conflicts and resettling of tribes and ethnicities, of which the [[Shina people|Dardic Shina]] race is the most prominent in regional history. People of the region have recounted their historical traditions down the generations. The Hunza Valley is also home to some [[Wakhi people|Wakhi]], who migrated there from northeastern Afghanistan beginning in the nineteenth century onwards.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Arts and Crafts of the Hunza Valley in Pakistan: Living Traditions in the Karakoram|last=Frembgen Wasim|first=Jurgen|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2017|isbn=978-0-19-940520-6|location=Karachi|pages=1}}</ref>\n\nThe longevity of Hunza people has been noted by some,<ref name=\"Wrench1938\">{{Cite book |year=1938 |author=Wrench, Dr Guy T |title=The Wheel of Health: A Study of the Hunza People and the Keys to Health |series=2009 reprint |place= |publisher=Review Press |isbn=978-0-9802976-6-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMfSuHgabYoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=wheel+of+health#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010 }}</ref> but others refute this as a [[Longevity myths|longevity myth]] and cite a life expectancy of 110 years for men and 122 for women with a high standard deviation.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C02E2D9173CF93AA1575AC0A960958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 | work=The New York Times | title=The Optimists Are Right | first=John | last=Tierney | date=29 September 1996}}</ref> There is no evidence that Hunza life expectancy is significantly above the average of poor, isolated regions of Pakistan. Claims of health and long life were almost always based solely on the statements by the local mir (king). An author who had significant and sustained contact with Burusho people, John Clark, reported that they were overall unhealthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblelife.org/hunza.htm|title=Hunza \u2013 The Truth, Myths, and Lies About the Health and Diet of the \"Long-Lived\" People of Hunza, Pakistan, Hunza Bread and Pie Recipes.|website=www.biblelife.org}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[State of Hunza|State of Hunza (former)]]\n* [[Hunza\u2013Nagar District]]\n* [[Bagrot Valley]]\n* [[Naltar Valley]]\n* [[Shamanism in Hunza]]\n* [[Northern Areas|Northern Areas (former)]]\n* [[Silk Road transmission of Buddhism]]\n* [[Karakoram Highway]]\n* [[Karakoram Mountains]]\n* [[Neelam Valley]]\n* [[Kalasha Valley]]\n* [[Kaghan Valley]]\n* [[Nagar Valley]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Kreutzmann, Hermann, ''Karakoram in Transition: Culture, Development, and Ecology in the Hunza Valley'', Oxford University Press, 2006. {{ISBN|978-0-19-547210-3}}\n* Leitner, G. W. (1893): ''Dardistan in 1866, 1886 and 1893: Being An Account of the History, Religions, Customs, Legends, Fables and Songs of Gilgit, Chilas, Kandia (Gabrial) Yasin, Chitral, Hunza, Nagar and other parts of the Hindukush, as also a supplement to the second edition of The Hunza and Nagar Handbook. And An Epitome of Part III of the author\u2019s \u201cThe Languages and Races of Dardistan.\u201d'' First Reprint 1978. Manjusri Publishing House, New Delhi.\n* Lorimer, Lt. Col. D.L.R. ''Folk Tales of Hunza''. 1st edition 1935, Oslo. Three volumes. Vol. II, republished by the Institute of Folk Heritage, Islamabad. 1981.\n* Sidkey, M. H. \"Shamans and Mountain Spirits in Hunza.\" ''Asian Folklore Studies'', Vol. 53, No. 1 (1994), pp.&nbsp;67\u201396.\n* [https://hisamullah.wordpress.com/2012/04/29/tarikh-e-ehd-e-ateeq-e-riasat-e-hunza-english-translation/ History of Ancient Era Hunza State] By Haji Qudratullah Beg English Translation By Lt Col (Rtd) Saadullah Beg, TI(M)\n* {{citation |year=1938 |author=Wrench, Dr Guy T |title=The Wheel of Health: A Study of the Hunza People and the Keys to Health |series=2009 reprint |place= |publisher=Review Press |isbn=978-0-9802976-6-9 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lMfSuHgabYoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=wheel+of+health#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010}}\n* Miller, Katherine, 'Schooling Virtue: Education for 'Spiritual Development' in Megan Adamson Sijapati and Jessica Vantine Birkenholtz, eds., Religion and Modernity in the Himalaya (London: Routledge, 2016).\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Hunza Valley}}\n\n* http://emergingpakistan.gov.pk/travel/place-to-visit/gilgit-baltistan/hunza-valley/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category: Valleys of Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n[[Category: Hunza]]\n[[Category: History of Gilgit Agency]]\n[[Category: Hindu Kush]]\n[[Category: Himalayas]]\n[[Category: Regions of Pakistan]]\n[[Category: Landslides in 2010]]\n[[Category: Valleys of Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the article about the former princely state|Hunza (princely state)}}\n{{original research|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name               = Hunza Valley\n| ot